setwd("~/Dropbox/Projects/OSCR/ML_Lab1/Markdown")
football_train <- read.csv("~/Dropbox/Projects/OSCR/ML_Lab1/Datasets/football_train.csv")
football_test <- read.csv("~/Dropbox/Projects/OSCR/ML_Lab1/Datasets/football_test.csv")

Tree Based Method (1) CART

tree_mod <- tree(Wins~. - ID, data = football_train)
plot(tree_mod)
text(tree_mod, cex = 0.6)

We interpret the tree diagram as following: For a team with opprushing attempt less than 441.5, interceptionsThrown less than 11.5, OppTurnOversLost less than 20.5, we predict the win to be 9.417.

As we can see, such tree model can be easily interpreted. But how does it perform in terms of predictability? We predict the testing set using this tree model.

pred_tree <- predict(tree_mod, newdata = football_test)
rmse(actual = football_answers$Wins, predicted = pred_tree)
## [1] 2.327869

We found our prediction RMSE to be 2.32. Could it be possible that our model is overfitting the training data?

Remember from our previous post, we discussed CARTs propensity to overfit: Overfitting happens when a model memorizes its training data so well that it is learning noise on top of the signal. The CART algorithm will repeatedly partition data into smaller and smaller subsets until those final subsets contain only a small set of observations (1 or 2).

We observe that our CART tree is very complex, it is likly overfitted. Could we further improve RMSE by using cross validation and pruning? The goal of pruning is to attain minimum error. The tree is pruned back to the point where the cross-validated error is a minimum. Cross-validation is the process of building a tree with most of the data and then using the remaining part of the data to test the accuracy of the decision tree.

set.seed (2) ## We split the original training set to training and testing to 75% and 25%. However, we don't have to so sampling in our example due to the dataset owner providing training and testing data
smp_size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(football_train))
train_samp=sample(1: nrow(football_train),size = smp_size)
train=football_train[train_samp,]
test=football_train[-train_samp,]

The pruning can be easily achieved by calling the cv.tree function

cv.tree =cv.tree(tree_mod,FUN=prune.tree, K=10)
plot(cv.tree$size ,cv.tree$dev ,type="b")

From the plot of deviance VS size of tree, we found that the size that leads to minimum cross validation deviance is 6. We prune and plot the tree accordingly. We also found that as the size of tree increases, the deviance increases.

prune.tree =prune.tree(tree_mod ,best = 6) ## best specifies the size that gives minimum deviance
plot(prune.tree)
text(prune.tree, cex = 0.8)

## Comparing with our original tree
plot(tree_mod)
text(tree_mod, cex = 0.8)

## Predicting with pruned tree
pred_tree_prune <- predict(prune.tree, newdata = football_test)
rmse(actual = football_answers$Wins, predicted = pred_tree_prune) ## the pruned prediction
## [1] 2.265582
rmse(actual = football_answers$Wins, predicted = pred_tree) ## the original prediction
## [1] 2.327869

Comparing our orginal tree with the pruned tree, we found that pruned tree has much fewer branches (complexities) and our model accuracy (RMSE) dropped from 2.32 to 2.26. This shows that our original CART was overfitting!

Tree Based Method (2) Random Forest

Now you understand Classification and Regression Trees, we introduce two algorithms that utilizes and improves upon the traditional CART. The first is Random forest, like its name implies, consists of a large number of individual decision trees that operate as an ensemble. For classification proble, each individual tree in the random forest spits out a class prediction and the class with the most votes becomes our models prediction; for regression, the predicted response is the average of the prediction from each tree.

We build the model using the function randomForest. Notice the command importance = TRUE this specifies that the importance of predictors should be assessed.

rf_mod <- randomForest(Wins~. - ID, data = football_train, importance = TRUE)
varImpPlot (rf_mod, cex = 0.5)

We predict our result using random forest and plot the variable importance. You might be wondering how each of the variable importance is calculated:

Accuracy-based importance: using out-of-bag samples (left)

  • prediction accuracy on the out-of-bag sample is measured.
  • the values of the variable in the out-of-bag-sample are randomly shuffled, keeping all other variables the same.
  • the decrease in prediction accuracy on the shuffled data is measured. (the variable that leads to the highest increase MSE is most important)

Gini-based importance (right)

  • For each variable, the sum of the Gini decrease across every tree of the forest is accumulated every time that variable is chosen to split a node.
  • The sum is divided by the number of trees in the forest to give an average.
  • The larger the gini-based average, the more important the variable
pred_rf <- predict(rf_mod, newdata = football_test)
rmse(actual = football_answers$Wins, predicted = pred_rf)
## [1] 1.634703

We found that Random forest again decreased our prediction error from 2.16 to 1.63. However, its interpretability suffers because we can no longer plot all the tree and intepret the results. Random Forest RMSE represent the performance of bagged tree. How does gradient boosted tree XGBoost and LightGBM perform?

Tree Based Method (3) XGBoost

Random Forest is an example of tree ensemble. In this section, we will introduce another decision tree based ensemble machine learning algorithm that uses gradient boosting frame work: XGBoost. - Boosting models are built sequentially by minimizing the errors from previous models while increasing (or boosting) influence of high performance models. - Gradient boosting models employs gradient descent algorithms to minimize errors in sequential models. - XGBoost optimized gradient boosting algorithm through parallel processing, tree_pruning, handling missing balues and regularization to avoid overfitting and bias, while also drastically decreasing the run time. (like gradient boosting models on steroids! )

Code: For XGBoost, we need to first convert the predictors into xgb.Dmatrix format, then we use xgboost function to model.

train_values <- football_train[, !(names(football_train) == 'Wins' | names(football_train) == 'ID')] 
train_result <- football_train$Wins
test_values <- football_test[, !(names(football_test) == 'ID')]
test_result <- football_answers$Wins
dtrain = xgb.DMatrix(data =  as.matrix(train_values), label = train_result)
dtest = xgb.DMatrix(data =  as.matrix(test_values), label = test_result)
watchlist = list(train=dtrain, test=dtest)
## training the XGBoost tree without tuning the parameter
model_xgb <- xgboost(data = dtrain, missing = NA, max.depth = 6, eta = 0.3, nthread = 4, nrounds = 16, verbose = 2, objective = "reg:linear")

pred_xg <- predict(model_xgb , newdata = dtest)

Hmmmm It seems that XGBoost doesnt perform as well as random forest. However, the variable selection are similar for Random Forest and XGBoost.

The Package CARET

The caret package (short for Classification And REgression Training) is a set of functions that attempt to streamline the process for creating predictive models. The package contains tools for:

data splitting pre-processing feature selection model tuning using resampling variable importance estimation
